<exercises>
  <title>Exercises</title>

<exercise xml:id="mv-mcq-1">
  <title>Understanding the Basic Model</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      The differential equation for a mass–spring–damper system is
      <m>m x'' + c x' + k x = F(t)</m>.  
      What does the constant <m>c</m> represent?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p>The damping coefficient.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. <m>c \ge 0</m> is the friction/damping term.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>The spring stiffness.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—that is <m>k</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>The external forcing strength.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—forcing is represented by <m>F(t)</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>
  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="mv-mcq-2">
  <title>Forced vs. Unforced Motion</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      In the model <m>m x'' + c x' + k x = F(t)</m>, when is the motion called <em>unforced</em>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p>When <m>F(t) \equiv 0</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. If <m>F(t)</m> is identically zero, the motion is unforced (free).
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>When <m>c=0</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—that corresponds to undamped, not unforced.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>When <m>k=0</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—that would eliminate the spring.</p></feedback>
    </choice>
  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="mv-mcq-3">
  <title>Damped vs. Undamped</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      In the ODE <m>m x'' + c x' + k x = 0</m>, how do we know whether the system is damped?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p>If <m>c &gt; 0</m>, the motion is damped.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. <m>c &gt; 0</m> means damping is present.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>If <m>m=0</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—a mass must be positive in the model.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>If <m>k=0</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—the spring constant has nothing to do with damping.</p></feedback>
    </choice>
  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="mv-mcq-4">
  <title>Qualitative Behavior of Undamped Motion</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the unforced, undamped equation <m>m x'' + k x = 0</m>.  
      What type of motion does it describe?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p>Simple harmonic oscillations with constant amplitude.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. With <m>c=0</m> and <m>F(t)=0</m>, the solution is sinusoidal.  
          This is undamped harmonic motion.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>Damped oscillations that decay over time.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—that requires <m>c>0</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>Exponential growth without oscillations.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—the restoring force <m>k x</m> prevents runaway motion.</p></feedback>
    </choice>
  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="mv-mcq-5">
  <title>Natural Frequency</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      For the undamped, unforced system <m>m x'' + k x = 0</m>, the angular frequency of oscillation is
      <m>\omega = \sqrt{\frac{k}{m}}</m>.  
      If <m>m = 4</m> and <m>k = 36</m>, what is <m>\omega</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>\omega = 3</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct.  
          <m>\omega = \sqrt{36/4} = \sqrt{9} = 3.</m>  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>\omega = 6</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>This corresponds to forgetting the division by <m>m</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>\omega = \sqrt{40}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Incorrect substitution into the formula.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="spring-mass-dashpot">
  <statement>

    <p>
      Consider the spring–mass system shown in <xref ref="SpringMass4"/>.  
      An object of mass <m>m</m> is attached to a spring with spring constant <m>k</m>, 
      and a dashpot provides damping with coefficient <m>c</m>.  
      If <m>x(t)</m> denotes displacement from equilibrium, then
    </p>

    <men xml:id="dashpoteqn">
      m \frac{d^{2}x}{dt^{2}} + c \frac{dx}{dt} + kx = 0.
    </men>

    <figure xml:id="SpringMass4" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
      <caption>A dashpot.</caption>
      <image source="SpringMass4.jpg" width="50%">
        <description>
          A mass–spring–dashpot system: a wall on the left, a spring attached to a block of mass m,
          and a damper connected from the block to another wall.
        </description>
      </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
      A <term>dashpot</term> exerts a resistive force proportional to the velocity.  
      We investigate several cases of the equation depending on <m>m</m>, <m>c</m>, and <m>k</m>.
    </p>

    <ol marker="(a)">

      <li>
        <p>
          <alert>Undamped Motion.</alert>  
          Suppose <m>c=0</m>.  
          Then the model becomes  
        </p>
        <me>
          m x'' + kx = 0.
        </me>
        <p>
          With <m>\omega_0 = \sqrt{k/m}</m>:
        </p>

        <ol marker="(i)">
          <li>
            <p>Find the characteristic equation and its roots.</p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Find the general solution <m>x(t)</m> written in terms of <m>\omega_0</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          <alert>Undamped Motion (Example).</alert>  
          A mass <m>m=\tfrac12</m> kg is attached to a spring that is stretched 2 m by a force of 100 N.  
          Initial conditions: <m>x(0)=1</m>, <m>x'(0)=-5</m>.
        </p>

        <ol marker="(i)">
          <li><p>Find the spring constant <m>k</m> and write the resulting DE.</p></li>

          <li><p>Interpret the differential equation in words.</p></li>

          <li><p>Explain what the initial conditions mean physically.</p></li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Given <m>\omega_0 = 10</m>, the solution is  
              <m>x(t) = \cos(10t) - \tfrac12 \sin(10t)</m>.  
              Compute the frequency <m>\nu = \omega_0/(2\pi)</m> and the period <m>T</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Convert <m>x(t) = c_1 \cos(\omega_0 t) + c_2 \sin(\omega_0 t)</m> into  
              <m>x(t) = A \cos(\omega_0 t - \phi)</m>.
            </p>

            <ol marker="(A)">
              <li><p>Compute <m>A = \sqrt{c_1^2 + c_2^2}</m>.</p></li>
              <li><p>Compute <m>\phi</m> from <m>\tan\phi = c_2/c_1</m> (noting it lies in quadrant IV).</p></li>
            </ol>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              The first peak occurs at <m>t^* = \phi/\omega_0</m>.  
              Determine <m>t^*</m> and describe/sketch the motion.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          With damping (<m>c &gt; 0</m>), the characteristic equation is  
        </p>
        <me>
          m r^2 + c r + k = 0,
        </me>
        <p>
          with roots  
        </p>
        <me>
          r = \frac{-c \pm \sqrt{c^2 - 4mk}}{2m}.
        </me>

        <ul>
          <li><term>Overdamped:</term> <m>c^2 &gt; 4mk</m></li>
          <li><term>Critically damped:</term> <m>c^2 = 4mk</m></li>
          <li><term>Underdamped:</term> <m>c^2 &lt; 4mk</m></li>
        </ul>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p><term>Overdamped Motion.</term> Assume <m>c^2 &gt; 4mk</m>.</p>

        <ol marker="(i)">
          <li>
            <p>
              Explain why both roots <m>r_1,r_2</m> are negative.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Give the general solution.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Compute <m>\lim_{t\to\infty} x(t)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p><term>Critically Damped Motion.</term>  Assume <m>c^2 = 4mk</m>.</p>

        <ol marker="(i)">
          <li>
            <p>
              Explain why the repeated root is <m>r=-c/(2m)</m> and why it is negative.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li><p>Give the general solution.</p></li>

          <li><p>Compute <m>\lim_{t\to\infty} x(t)</m>.</p></li>
        </ol>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          <term>Underdamped Motion.</term>  
          Suppose <m>c=1</m>, <m>m=\tfrac12</m>, <m>k=50</m>.
        </p>

        <ol marker="(i)">
          <li><p>Find the complex roots of the characteristic equation.</p></li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Given the solution  
            </p>
            <me>
              x(t) = e^{-t}\!\Bigl( \cos(\sqrt{99}t) 
              - \frac{4}{\sqrt{99}}\sin(\sqrt{99}t) \Bigr),
            </me>
            <p>
              Compute <m>\lim_{t\to\infty} x(t)</m> and describe the qualitative shape of the graph.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </li>

    </ol>
  </statement>

  <solution>

    <p><strong>(a) Undamped Motion (c = 0)</strong></p>

    <ol marker="(i)">
      <li>
        <p>
          The DE is  
          <m>m x'' + kx = 0</m>.  
          Characteristic equation:
        </p>
        <me>
          mr^{2} + k = 0
          \quad\Rightarrow\quad
          r^{2} = -\frac{k}{m}.
        </me>
        <p>
          Thus <m>r = \pm i\sqrt{k/m} = \pm i\omega_0</m>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          The general solution is
        </p>
        <me>
          x(t) = C_1 \cos(\omega_0 t) + C_2 \sin(\omega_0 t).
        </me>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p><strong>(b) Undamped Example</strong></p>

    <ol marker="(i)">
      <li>
        <p>
          Hooke’s law: a force of 100 N stretches the spring 2 m, so  
        </p>
        <me>
          k = \frac{100}{2} = 50.
        </me>
        <p>
          The DE is  
        </p>
        <me>
          \tfrac12 x'' + 50 x = 0
          \quad\Rightarrow\quad
          x'' + 100 x = 0.
        </me>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>The DE states: acceleration is proportional to displacement toward equilibrium.</p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          The initial conditions mean the mass starts 1 m to the right of equilibrium and moving left at 5 m/s.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Frequency:  
        </p>
        <me>
          \nu = \omega_{0}/(2\pi) = 10/(2\pi) = \frac{5}{\pi} \approx 1.59\ \text{Hz}.
        </me>
        <p>Period:</p>
        <me>
          T = 1/\nu = \frac{\pi}{5} \approx 0.628.
        </me>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Here <m>c_1 = 1</m>, <m>c_2 = -\tfrac12</m>.
        </p>
        <ol marker="(A)">
          <li>
            <md>
              <mrow> A \amp = \sqrt{1^2 + \left(-\tfrac12\right)^2} </mrow>
               <mrow> \amp = \sqrt{1 + \tfrac14} </mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = \sqrt{\tfrac54} </mrow>
               <mrow> \amp = \tfrac{\sqrt5}{2}. </mrow>
            </md>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\tan\phi = c_2/c_1 = -\tfrac12</m>.  
              Quadrant IV → <m>\phi \approx -0.46365</m> radians  
              or equivalently <m>\phi = 2\pi - 0.46365 \approx 5.8195</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Time lag:
        </p>
        <me>
          t^{*} = \phi/\omega_{0} \approx 5.8195 / 10 = 0.58195.
        </me>
        <p>
          The graph is a cosine‑like oscillation of amplitude <m>A</m> and frequency <m>\nu</m>, shifted right.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p><strong>(c) Overdamped Motion</strong></p>

    <ol marker="(i)">
      <li>
        <p>
          For <m>c^{2} &gt; 4mk</m>,  
          <m>r = \frac{-c \pm \sqrt{c^{2}-4mk}}{2m}</m>.  
          Since <m>c &gt; \sqrt{c^{2}-4mk} &gt; 0</m>, both numerator terms are negative ⇒ both roots negative.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          General solution:
        </p>
        <me>
          x(t) = C_1 e^{r_1 t} + C_2 e^{r_2 t}
          \quad (r_1,r_2 &lt; 0).
        </me>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Limit:
        </p>
        <me>
          \lim_{t\to\infty} x(t) = 0.
        </me>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p><strong>(d) Critically Damped Motion</strong></p>

    <ol marker="(i)">
      <li>
        <p>
          If <m>c^2 = 4mk</m>,  
          <m>r = \frac{-c}{2m}</m>.  
          Since <m>c &gt; 0,m &gt; 0</m>, the root is negative.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          General solution:
        </p>
        <me>
          x(t) = (C_1 + C_2 t)e^{rt}.
        </me>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Limit:
        </p>
        <me>
          \lim_{t\to\infty} x(t) = 0.
        </me>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p><strong>(e) Underdamped Motion</strong></p>

    <ol marker="(i)">
      <li>
        <p>
          Characteristic equation:
        </p>
        <me>
          \tfrac12 r^{2} + 1 r + 50 = 0.
        </me>
        <p>
          Multiply by 2: <m>r^{2} + 2r + 100 = 0</m>.  
          Roots:
        </p>
        <me>
          r = -1 \pm i\sqrt{99}.
        </me>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          For the solution
        </p>
        <me>
          x(t) = e^{-t}\!\left( \cos\sqrt{99}t - \frac{4}{\sqrt{99}}\sin\sqrt{99}t \right),
        </me>
        <p>
          the exponential factor dominates:
        </p>
        <me>
          \lim_{t\to\infty} x(t) = 0.
        </me>

        <p>
          Qualitatively, the plot shows oscillations whose amplitude decays exponentially.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>

  </solution>
</exercise>

</exercises>

</section>

      <section xml:id="sec-Advancedlearningobjectives24">
        <title>Advanced learning objectives</title>

        <p>
          In addition to mastering the basic objectives, here are the tasks you should be able 
          to perform, with practice:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
      Analyze how changing <em>parameters</em> <m>m, c, k</m> affects system behavior, including oscillations and decay rates.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
      Translate physical laws (Newton’s second law or Kirchhoff’s laws) into corresponding differential 
      equations for mechanical and electrical systems.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
      Extend the vibration framework to approximate models such as pendulum motion and interpret when linearization is appropriate.
            </p>
          </li>

        </ul>

      </section>


</handout>